WEBVTT

00:00:01.280 --> 00:00:05.920
<v Teacher>We said that the word for <i>always</i> was <b>siempre</b>.

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:06.720
<v Student><b>Siempre.</b>

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:07.280
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:14.960
<v Teacher>Now if you know Italian or some other Latin language, maybe you have something like <b>sempre</b>

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:19.940
<v Teacher>in that language, and you can see again that the <i>e</i> is splitting between <b>sempre</b> and <b>siempre</b>.

00:00:19.940 --> 00:00:25.380
<v Teacher>So if you know one of these other languages, or have studied them, it can be useful just to notice that.

00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:28.980
<v Teacher>And just noticing that helps you internalize this new word.

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:35.000
<v Teacher>So for example, <i>well</i> in Spanish is <b>bien</b> like in the beginning of <i>welcome</i>, <b>bienvenido</b>.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.240
<v Teacher>This in Italian is <b>bene</b>.

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:41.720
<v Teacher>We see that we get rid of the <i>e</i>, the last <i>e</i>, and the <i>e</i> in the middle splits.

00:00:41.540 --> 00:00:44.180
<v Teacher>You have from French <b>bon</b> for <i>good</i>.

00:00:44.180 --> 00:00:47.620
<v Teacher>What do you think <i>good</i> might be in Spanish?

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:50.660
<v Teacher>What do you think you will do to make that more Spanish?

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:51.540
<v Student><b>Bueno.</b>

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:52.180
<v Teacher>Bueno.

00:00:53.079 --> 00:01:00.039
<v Teacher>We also said that vamos meant we are going or let's go, and it's something you're gonna hear all the time.

00:01:00.039 --> 00:01:01.800
<v Teacher><b>Vamos, vamos</b>, <i>let's go</i>.

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:09.500
<v Teacher>Now, another useful skill that we want in language learning is to work backwards, not just to work from the “to” form,

00:01:09.660 --> 00:01:24.460
<v Teacher>take off the - <i>ar</i> or the -<i>er</i> or -<i>ir</i> and add bits on. But we want to get in the habit of also working backwards, because maybe we see or hear somewhere a word like <b>vamos,</b> and we want to be able to work backwards from <b>vamos</b> to get the other versions.

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:29.120
<v Teacher>Taking off the ending which is for <i>we</i>, and putting our other bits on.

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:38.880
<v Teacher>So could you work out from <b>vamos</b> how it would be <i>he goes </i>or <i>is going, she goes </i>or <i>is going</i>, <i>you</i> (formal) <i>go </i>or <i>are going</i>?

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:42.320
<v Student>The thing is you don't know the ending of the “to" form.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:47.120
<v Teacher>If you have -<i>amos</i>, you know which is your vowel, no?

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:48.240
<v Student>/<i>a</i>/.

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:49.360
<v Teacher>/<i>a</i>/. So, work backwards.

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:52.800
<v Student>Ah, yes, okay, so <b>va</b>?

00:01:52.700 --> 00:01:58.220
<v Teacher><b>Va.</b> What does that mean? <b>Va</b>:

00:02:00.740 --> 00:02:04.900
<v Student><i>He/she/it</i> or <i>you</i> (formal) <i>are going</i>.

00:02:04.900 --> 00:02:05.460
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:11.700
<v Teacher><b>Va.</b> How would you make that <i>you</i> (informal)?

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:13.720
<v Student><b>Vas.</b>

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:15.000
<v Teacher><b>Vas.</b> Good.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.840
<v Teacher>If you want to say <i>where are you going</i>, you will hear <i>to where are you going?</i>

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:21.800
<v Teacher>What was the word for <i>to</i>?

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:22.360
<v Student><b>A.</b>

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:25.560
<v Teacher><b>A.</b> So how would you say <i>To where are you going?</i>:

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:32.600
<v Student><b>¿A dónde vas?</b>

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:34.020
<v Teacher>¿<b>A dónde vas?</b> What would be <i>they go</i>? Or <i>you</i> (plural) <i>go</i>:

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:34.819
<v Student><b>Van.</b>

00:02:34.819 --> 00:02:35.700
<v Teacher>Van.

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:36.420
<v Teacher>Van.

00:02:36.420 --> 00:02:36.819
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:36.819 --> 00:02:38.420
<v Teacher>So we can work backwards.

00:02:38.420 --> 00:02:41.220
<v Teacher><b>Vamos-va-vas-van</b>.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:47.540
<v Teacher>What was the <i>I</i> version? It was irregular and we remembered it by thinking <i>I'm going on a voyage</i>:

00:02:47.760 --> 00:02:48.480
<v Student><b>Voy.</b>

00:02:48.480 --> 00:02:49.680
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:53.840
<v Teacher>Now the “to” form <i>to go</i> is <b>ir</b>.

00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:55.840
<v Teacher><i>I-r</i> all by itself:

00:02:55.840 --> 00:02:56.640
<v Teacher><b>ir</b>.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:58.319
<v Teacher>This is <i>to go</i>.

00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:09.239
<v Teacher>So it's very irregular. And this is actually because this verb is two verbs that kind of stuck together to form one verb over time.

00:03:09.480 --> 00:03:19.160
<v Teacher>So in French you have like <b>aller</b>, which means <i>going</i>, and in English we get <i>alleyway</i> from this. An <i>alleyway</i> is like a road, no?

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:20.760
<v Teacher>And this is related to <b>ir</b>.

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:30.000
<v Teacher>So <b>ir</b> comes from one verb, historically. And then the versions of <b>ir</b> actually come from a different verb.

00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:34.500
<v Teacher>So they kind of stuck together over time and they give us this very irregular situation.

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:36.980
<v Teacher>That's just for interest, we don't need to know any of this.

00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:44.260
<v Teacher>All we need to know is <b>voy</b> from <i>voyage</i> and <b>vamos</b> and we can work backwards from <b>vamos</b> and there we have the complete set.

00:03:43.660 --> 00:03:46.620
<v Teacher><b>Voy, vamos, va, vas, van</b>.

00:03:46.620 --> 00:03:49.180
<v Teacher>But <i>to go i</i>s <b>ir</b>.

00:03:49.180 --> 00:03:56.860
<v Teacher>they are coming from two different verbs historically, which is why we have <b>ir</b>, which is an -<i>ir</i> verb, but <i>a</i> coming up for all of the different versions.

00:03:56.560 --> 00:03:59.599
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I want to go</i>?

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:00.560
<v Student><b>Quiero ir.</b>

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:00.959
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:00.959 --> 00:04:04.720
<v Teacher><i>I can go</i>. <i>I have the power to go</i>:

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:05.680
<v Student><b>Puedo ir.</b>

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:06.000
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:07.760
<v Teacher><i>I must go</i>:

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:09.440
<v Student><b>Debo ir.</b>

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:10.560
<v Teacher>Debo ir.

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:11.600
<v Teacher>I have to go.

00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:12.880
<v Teacher>So not <i>I must go</i>,

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:13.920
<v Teacher><b>debo ir</b>;

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:15.200
<v Teacher><i>I have to go</i>.

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:18.240
<v Teacher>What is <i>I have</i> from <b>tener</b>?

00:04:18.760 --> 00:04:19.560
<v Student><b>Tengo.</b>

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:20.040
<v Teacher>Tengo.

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:22.600
<v Teacher>And what do we add to that to get the meaning of <i>have to</i>?

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:24.520
<v Student><b>A</b>?

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:28.920
<v Teacher><b>Que</b>. Like I said there's no comfortable translation for it,

00:04:28.780 --> 00:04:34.620
<v Teacher>but we add on <b>que</b> to <b>tengo</b> and we get the feeling of “have to" rather than the feeling of possession.

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:37.340
<v Teacher>So <i>I have to go</i>:

00:04:37.420 --> 00:04:38.620
<v Student><b>Tengo que ir.</b>

00:04:38.620 --> 00:04:39.580
<v Teacher>Tengo que ir.

00:04:39.580 --> 00:04:40.620
<v Teacher>I have to go now:

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:43.460
<v Student><b>Tengo que ir ahora.</b>

00:04:43.460 --> 00:04:43.940
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:43.940 --> 00:04:46.419
<v Teacher>The word for <i>tonight</i> is <i>this night</i>:

00:04:46.419 --> 00:04:48.020
<v Teacher><b>esta noche</b>.

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:53.860
<v Teacher>So <i>I have to go tonight, I have to go this night</i>:

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.200
<v Student><b>Tengo que ir esta noche.</b>

00:04:57.200 --> 00:04:59.040
<v Teacher>Now <b>noche</b> is feminine.

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:03.200
<v Teacher>We know this because <b>esta</b>, the word for <i>this</i>, is ending in an <i>a</i>.

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:05.360
<v Teacher>So how would you say: <i>the night</i>?

00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:06.979
<v Student><b>La noche.</b>

00:05:06.979 --> 00:05:08.020
<v Teacher>La noche.

00:05:08.020 --> 00:05:18.259
<v Teacher>So we said that words ending a are feminine, or there are feminine endings like -ión or -idad. La opinión, la oportunidad.

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:24.240
<v Teacher>If it ends in an e, there's actually no way of knowing whether it's masculine or feminine by the word.

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:26.080
<v Teacher>You have to look up what's around it,

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:27.680
<v Teacher>or in the dictionary it will tell you.

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:30.960
<v Teacher>But if you hear it in conversation, you have a look at what's around it,

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:34.700
<v Teacher><b>esta noche</b>, and then you can go oh okay, so<b> noche </b>is feminine.

00:05:34.700 --> 00:05:38.860
<v Teacher>Another example of a feminine word that ends in an e is carne,

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:39.740
<v Teacher>carne.

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:41.820
<v Teacher>What do you think <b>carne</b> means?

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:43.900
<v Teacher>It's not at all obvious.

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:47.160
<v Teacher>You have <i>carnage</i> in English.

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:49.080
<v Teacher>It was just <i>carnage</i>.

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:51.160
<v Teacher><b>Carne</b> is <i>meat</i>.

00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:52.280
<v Teacher><i>Meat.</i>

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:53.560
<v Teacher>And it's a feminine word.

00:05:53.560 --> 00:05:55.080
<v Teacher>So <i>the meat</i>:

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:56.940
<v Student><b>La carne.</b>

00:05:56.940 --> 00:05:57.820
<v Teacher>La carne.

00:05:57.820 --> 00:06:00.060
<v Teacher>I don't eat meat:

00:06:00.380 --> 00:06:02.060
<v Student><b>No como carne.</b>

00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:03.340
<v Teacher>No como carne.

00:06:03.340 --> 00:06:05.020
<v Teacher>The word for <i>and</i> in Spanish is <b>y</b>.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:08.840
<v Teacher>And it's just spelt with a <i>y</i> by itself. <b>Y</b>.

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:10.360
<v Student><b>Y</b>.

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:14.520
<v Teacher>I don't eat meat and I don't drink, or I don't take,

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:15.440
<v Teacher>alcohol.

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:20.320
<v Teacher>So <b>tomar</b> was <i>to take</i>, <b>tomar</b>. And <b>comer</b>, <i>to eat</i>.

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:28.480
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I don't eat meat, and I don't take alcohol</i>? <i>I don't drink </i> <i>alcohol</i>.

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:31.500
<v Student><b>No como carne.</b>

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:32.500
<v Teacher><i>And</i>:

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:33.500
<v Student><b>Y.</b>

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:36.060
<v Teacher><i>I don't drink alcohol</i>:

00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:41.660
<v Student><b>No tomo</b> <i>alcohol -</i> <b>alcohol.</b>

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:45.420
<v Teacher><b>Alcohol.</b> Good. Because we don't pronounce <i>h</i> in Spanish, do we?

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:48.860
<v Teacher>No como carne y no tomo  alcohol.

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:56.200
<v Teacher>Or If you wanted to say I eat meat, and I take alcohol; I eat meat, and I drink alcohol, how would that be?

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:01.160
<v Student><b>Como carne y tomo alcohol.</b>

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:01.800
<v Teacher>Good.
